¶ And the \nd LORD\nd* said, I have surely seen the affliction
of my people which \add are\add* in Egypt, and have heard their cry
by reason of their taskmasters; for I know their sorrows;

And Moses and Aaron did so, as the \nd LORD\nd* commanded;
and he lifted up the rod, and smote the waters that \add were\add*
in the river, in the sight of Pharaoh, and in the sight of his servants;
and all the waters that \add were\add* in the river were turned to
blood.

And they took ashes of the furnace, and stood before Pharaoh;
and Moses sprinkled it up toward heaven; and it became a boil breaking
forth \add with\add* blains upon man, and upon beast.

And this day shall be unto you for a memorial; and ye shall
keep it a feast to the \nd LORD\nd* throughout your generations;
ye shall keep it a feast by an ordinance for ever.

And the children of Israel did according to the word of Moses;
and they borrowed of the Egyptians jewels of silver, and jewels of
gold, and raiment:

The \nd LORD\nd* \add is\add* my strength and song, and he is become my
salvation: he \add is\add* my God, and I will prepare him an habitation;
my father’s God, and I will exalt him.

And Moses and Aaron said unto all the children of Israel, At
even, then ye shall know that the \nd LORD\nd* hath brought you out
from the land of Egypt:

When Jethro, the priest of Midian, Moses’ father in law, heard
of all that God had done for Moses, and for Israel his people, \add and\add*
that the \nd LORD\nd* had brought Israel out of Egypt;

¶ And Moses went out to meet his father in law, and did obeisance,
and kissed him; and they asked each other of \add their\add* welfare;
and they came into the tent.\f + \fr 18.7  \ft welfare: Heb. peace\f*

And Moses went up unto God, and the \nd LORD\nd* called unto him out of the
mountain, saying, Thus shalt thou say to the house of Jacob, and
tell the children of Israel;

Or if it be known that the ox hath used to push in time past,
and his owner hath not kept him in; he shall surely pay ox for ox;
and the dead shall be his own.

If the sun be risen upon him, \add there shall be\add* blood
\add shed\add* for him; \add for\add* he should make full restitution;
if he have nothing, then he shall be sold for his theft.

And this \add is\add* the offering which ye shall take of them;
gold, and silver, and brass,\f + \fr 25.3  \ft offering: or, heave
offering\f*

And I, behold, I have given with him Aholiab, the son of Ahisamach,
of the tribe of Dan: and in the hearts of all that are wise hearted
I have put wisdom, that they may make all that I have commanded thee;

And it shall come to pass, while my glory passeth by, that I will
put thee in a clift of the rock, and will cover thee with my hand
while I pass by:

Lest thou make a covenant with the inhabitants of the land,
and they go a whoring after their gods, and do sacrifice unto their
gods, and \add one\add* call thee, and thou eat of his sacrifice;

Thou shalt not offer the blood of my sacrifice with leaven;
neither shall the sacrifice of the feast of the passover be left
unto the morning.

¶ And Moses said unto the children of Israel, See, the \nd LORD\nd*
hath called by name Bezaleel the son of Uri, the son of Hur, of the
tribe of Judah;

And forty sockets of silver he made under the twenty boards;
two sockets under one board for his two tenons, and two sockets under
another board for his two tenons.

And he made thereunto four pillars \add of\add* shittim \add wood\add*,
and overlaid them with gold: their hooks \add were of\add* gold;
and he cast for them four sockets of silver.

And they made bells \add of\add* pure gold, and put the bells
between the pomegranates upon the hem of the robe, round about between
the pomegranates;
